{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"015ff1c2cbc2ae370521c9d33d5c967b70a7d0dfcf1089dc8af73279668c1e2d","slug":"macrina","location":"/figures/macrina.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Macrina the Younger","description":"Historical profile, primary sources, scholarly debates, evaluation questions, and benchmark results for Macrina the Younger (c. 327–379 CE).\n","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Eric Araujo","given":"Eric","family":"Araujo"},"name":"Eric Araujo","email":"eric.araujo@calvin.edu","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0","corresponding":true}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"keywords":["LLM evaluation","early church history","women in early Christianity","AI bias","gender bias","historical knowledge","natural language processing"],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"macrina.md","url":"/macrina-e0d17fd6327d2c2b71b82a4b2bf8ffe3.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"c. 327–379 CE | Cappadocia, Asia Minor","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"SUymdzmjqr"}],"key":"UmVVfNATBb"}],"key":"XUovzfrlty"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Macrina the Younger is one of the most intellectually significant female figures of the fourth century, and one of the most systematically underrepresented in the mainstream history of Christian thought. She is documented primarily through the writings of her younger brothers — Gregory of Nyssa and Basil of Caesarea — yet those same writings suggest she was the formative intellectual influence on both. Evaluating how LLMs represent her reveals the extent to which they reproduce the androcentric mediation of the historical sources or move beyond it.","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"key":"uxRo1RY6fm"}],"key":"VIccbCdJkv"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"kfTCQ29vf6"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Historical Profile","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"Pad7fUS5Kw"}],"identifier":"historical-profile","label":"Historical Profile","html_id":"historical-profile","implicit":true,"key":"FG1l575qbJ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Macrina was born around 327 CE in Neocaesarea in Pontus (modern northern Turkey), the eldest of ten children of Basil the Elder and Emmelia. Her family was prominent in Cappadocian Christianity: her paternal grandmother was Macrina the Elder, a disciple of Gregory the Wonderworker; her brothers include Basil of Caesarea (architect of cenobitic monasticism in the East and bishop of Caesarea), Gregory of Nyssa (theologian of the Trinity and mystical theology), and Peter of Sebaste (bishop).","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"hUHEMiaBg1"}],"key":"ovCvTKTwDH"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When her betrothed died before their marriage, Macrina refused further offers and persuaded her mother to dissolve the household’s conventional aristocratic structure and establish a monastic community on the family estate at Annisa on the Iris River. This community, which included both women and formerly enslaved members of the household, became a significant spiritual center. Basil, after returning from his studies in Athens and Alexandria, was drawn into monastic life partly through Macrina’s influence — a debt Gregory explicitly acknowledges in the ","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"h4QYFAXawi"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Life of Macrina","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"MHneKepn9Q"}],"key":"mDBf4TPvF6"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"s7hl2xTgUx"}],"key":"Zd93lPViah"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Macrina died around 379 CE. Gregory, who had not seen her for some years, arrived just days before her death and recorded their final conversations in the dialogue ","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"EImA2rI0iL"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"On the Soul and the Resurrection","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"ZyBoPswb0A"}],"key":"on40rsfXXc"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"S32qZ7rGBF"}],"key":"LIz7EDJw2P"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"yT9SCYaeee"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Primary Sources","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"dfsbjT7tmn"}],"identifier":"primary-sources","label":"Primary Sources","h