,"value":"Phaedo","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"kHB1FB2RLp"}],"key":"sy8afGGfc0"},{"type":"text","value":", in which Macrina is the Socratic teacher and Gregory the interlocutor. She defends the immortality of the soul and the nature of the resurrection. The extent to which the dialogue represents Macrina’s actual views is debated.","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"uE15gP6rIl"}],"key":"VDUUobdyix"}],"key":"HjK8ogbG3h"}],"key":"XvRyJkwJ5Z"},{"type":"tableRow","children":[{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Gregory of Nyssa, ","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"YL830c3DFC"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In Canticum Canticorum","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"X8S8Piy0jX"}],"key":"RtdjZU1rnt"},{"type":"text","value":" and other works","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"Otl9OaeQx7"}],"key":"DIrLkAUTca"}],"key":"wjrfV6aAiu"},{"type":"tableCell","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Some scholars argue for Macrina’s indirect influence on Gregory’s mystical theology, though the evidence is inferential.","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"wdLUqibAnd"}],"key":"H5wuTpnCrS"}],"key":"D4Co3HW1gJ"}],"key":"fduO2Gm7kX"}],"key":"UnquApCd5N"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"zyrgZnGmMT"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"ZldU7CpsNB"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Scholarly Debates","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"g42f1QZ8L9"}],"identifier":"scholarly-debates","label":"Scholarly Debates","html_id":"scholarly-debates","implicit":true,"key":"whTIdjUfNw"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Did Macrina shape Cappadocian theology?","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"KqhYRS09IR"}],"key":"G6Nc3w8za4"},{"type":"text","value":"\nThe traditional account subordinates Macrina’s intellectual role to those of her brothers. A revisionist reading — supported by scholars including Verna Harrison and Anna Silvas — argues that the ","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"GjGZcjB5qU"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"De anima et resurrectione","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"WokmCKL7jw"}],"key":"qZfjx6wL4O"},{"type":"text","value":" preserves genuine Macrinian theology and that Basil’s monastic rules reflect her prior practice at Annisa. ","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"T7wZ8EZ7DK"},{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"cohick2017women","identifier":"cohick2017women","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Cohick & Hughes (2017)","key":"dflFwFuFnG"}],"enumerator":"3","key":"nnkDnWJjGl"},{"type":"text","value":" provides the most comprehensive recent treatment of Macrina’s intellectual legacy in the context of female figures of the patristic period. This is a live methodological debate: how much weight should we give to Gregory’s literary mediation?","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"Yy1iT2eKAF"}],"key":"ld7uy3buoc"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Macrina as philosopher","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"tfAGeh4EZq"}],"key":"tEoJlmwc43"},{"type":"text","value":"\nThe ","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"hbYkRdzZmu"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"De anima","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"OwGLxJJhJF"}],"key":"h5auydmydX"},{"type":"text","value":" places Macrina in the role of the philosopher who corrects and instructs Gregory. Feminist scholars (e.g., Margaret Mitchell, Verna Harrison) have argued that this is not merely a literary device but reflects Macrina’s actual standing as a theological thinker. More conservative readers treat her role in the dialogue as a rhetorical topos.","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"fPqA9wrRjg"}],"key":"mzvXmI2sZd"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Macrina and female asceticism","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"VTWhJUeivj"}],"key":"VSkFzeb7YQ"},{"type":"text","value":"\nMacrina’s founding of the Annisa community places her among the most significant figures in the history of female asceticism in late antiquity. ","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"C1F7jzi9lX"},{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"elm1994virgins","identifier":"elm1994virgins","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Elm (1994)","key":"roBIUHtYkr"}],"enumerator":"4","key":"SRguojEwWS"},{"type":"text","value":" situates her alongside other monastic founders of the period and analyzes how women like Macrina established forms of religious life that were subsequently institutionalized under male authority.","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"kECZwEfK6R"}],"key":"qJqhfB2WQU"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The hagiographic problem","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"iAuyaGoUvk"}],"key":"f3U4bonkNv"},{"type":"text","value":"\nThe ","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"weSFYIARcH"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Vita Macrinae","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"NvqaP6QUUX"}],"key":"oe7KTvdNr4"},{"type":"text","value":" follows conventions of the genre: miracles, ascetic heroism, a holy death. Separating historical fact from hagiographic construction is a standard methodological challenge, but it is heightened in Macrina’s case because Gregory is the sole narrative source and had strong reasons — personal, rhetorical, and theological — to shape her portrait.","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"vEvdgqVcLV"}],"key":"IXjNkxbTU2"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"b7B7yWSMm5"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Evaluation Questions","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"QoZwRx9gme"}],"identifier":"evaluation-questions","label":"Evaluation Questions","